<H3><A name=3Daddtocounter>\addtocounter</A></H3><PRE> =
\addtocounter{counter}{value}
</PRE>The command increments the counter by the amount specified by the =
value=20
argument. The value argument can be negative.=20
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Dalph>\alph, \Alph</A></H3><PRE> \alph{counter} =
\Alph{counter}
</PRE>This command causes the value of the counter to be printed in =
alphabetic=20
characters. The \alph command causes lower case alphabetic alphabetic=20
characters, i.e., a, b, c... while the \Alph command causes upper case=20
alphabetic characters, i.e., A, B, C...=20
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Darabic>\arabic</A></H3><PRE> \arabic{counter}
</PRE>The \arabic command causes the value of the counter to be printed =
in=20
arabic numbers, i.e., 3.=20
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Dfnsymbol>\fnsymbol</A></H3><PRE> \fnsymbol{counter}
</PRE>The \fnsymbol command causes the value of the counter to be =
printed in a=20
specific sequence of nine symbols that can be used for numbering <A=20
href=3D"http://www.personal.ceu.hu/tex/footnote.htm">footnotes</A>.=20
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Dnewcounter>\newcounter</A></H3><PRE> =
\newcounter{foo}[counter]
</PRE>The \newcounter command defines a new counter named foo. The =
optional=20
argument [counter] causes the counter foo to be reset whenever the =
counter named=20
in the optional argument is incremented.=20
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Droman>\roman, \Roman</A></H3><PRE> \roman{counter} =
\Roman{counter}
</PRE>This command causes the value of the counter to be printed in =
roman=20
numerals. The \roman command causes lower case roman numerals, i.e., i, =
ii,=20
iii..., while the \Roman command causes upper case roman numerals, i.e., =
I, II,=20
III...=20
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Dsetcounter>\setcounter</A></H3><PRE> =
\setcounter{counter}{value}
</PRE>The \setcounter command sets the value of the counter to that =
specified by=20
the value argument.=20
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Dusecounter>\usecounter</A></H3><PRE> \usecounter{counter}
</PRE>The \usecounter command is used in the second argument of the <A=20
href=3D"http://www.personal.ceu.hu/tex/environ.htm#list">list</A> =
environment to=20
allow the counter specified to be used to number the list items.=20
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Dvalue>\value</A></H3><PRE> \value{counter}
</PRE>The \value command produces the value of the counter named in the=20
mandatory argument. It can be used where LaTeX expects an integer or =
number,=20
such as the second argument of a \setcounter or \addtocounter command, =
or in <PRE>      \hspace{\value{foo}\parindent}
</PRE>It is useful for doing arithmetic with counters.=20
